<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25043a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25043a">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25043a"> 43(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> children <font face="wake">G</font> creep thro / holed stone</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">A similar tradition is found attached to a <mark>holed stone</mark> near St Madrous&apos; Well, in Cornwall. There a block of granite, pierced in the centre by a hole, is called the &lsquo;<mark>Creeping Stone</mark>,&rsquo; because sickly <mark>children</mark> were passed through it to effect a cure. <small> J. F. M. Ffrench, <a name="JFPF" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#JFPF"><cite title="source">Prehistoric Faith and Worship</cite></a> (1912) 26-7</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: not copied </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
